 Flow description 2 
 1. new editor becomes aware of wiki
 1. decides to participate
 1. sees create new account or login
 1. clicks create new account
 1. is shown wikispot introduction unless wiki they came from has edited their own welcome. Look at how http://stackoverflow.com/ handles the process
 1. proceeds to sign up form
  1. picks username, is given feedback if their pick ends in numbers or includes certain phrases
  1. provides email address, explain that it must be valid email to proceed
  1. asked to fill out their introduction, examples are provided via link
 1. is sent email as soon as some editor has seen their introduction on recent changes and responded to it. These show up in recent changes as new Users/ page, but with different colored event tag
 1. is free to make edits, banner on page reminds them that their first 5 edits are not going live until another editor reviews them. They must collect their 5 approvals from different editors for them to count. So if someone approves their first five edits, then they still need to make 4 more that will be approved by 4 other editors.
 1. they make their first edit, it goes into Recent changes as suggestion or with some other edit tag.
 1. anyone who glances at it and doesnt think it abusive can click approve and it will be live on the page. If someone tries to edit a page with a pending suggestion they need to either accept or reject the suggestion. if rejecting a suggestion you have to explain why.
 1. repeat that process a couple more times and then grant them full editing



  I think this method has potential. Its not forcing anyone to approve or reject edits (unless they want to further edit the same page), its not restricting new editors from freely editing as they see fit, and it avoids the problems that IDoNotExist was mentioning about comments or other edits not showing up for some period of time.  JenniferCook

